nging interactions and transformations both within and between communities. Ultimately, she argues, the production and movement of luxury goods in the period demands a rethinking of our very geo-cultural conception of the Levant, as well as its influence beyond what have traditionally been thought of as its borders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDecorative arts, AncientzMiddle EastxHistory. 0aIron agezMiddle East. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  acollective memory, southwest asia, near eastern studies, art history, historical research, portable, luxury goods, artwork, iron age, society, culture, archeology, archeologist, historian, ivory, metal, community formation, middle east, antiquities, ancient, levantine style, mobility, identity, assyrianization, intentionality, levant, connoisseurship, assyria, babylonia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022610561140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226164427423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226164427/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles